[I received the following communication from Ross Tancred earlier this week.
In previous months he & I have discussed modern slaughter house hygiene and
meat inspection and it was very clear that he knew his job. MHJ]
From: Ross Tancred <rosst@meat.aust.com>
Subject: Q fever vaccine
Date: Tue, 25 Mar 1997 10:23:47 +1000
We operate a number of beef processing plants in Queensland, Australia, and
recently have had pressure put on us by the state Government Workplace
Health and Safety Authority to perform manditory tests and subsequent
vaccinations on all employees prior to commencment of work.
The current demand means visitors and new employees will be required to wear
respirators. This will really help us instill a view of how safe our meat
is to overseas visitors (after anthrax and salmonella this is wonderful) and
be realy practical for people working hard in a very manual industry. We are
of course challenging this "interesting" plan.
I thought this information may be usefull to some readers and I am
interested in hearing what other States and Countries require or what other
companies do in relation to this issue.
---
Ross Tancred
General Manager
Consolidated Meat Group
rosst@meat.aust.com
Ph. 61 79 305860
Fax 61 79 305869
[Having myself worked as a Meat Inspector in Calgary in the early '60s and
thus with first hand knowledge of how dangerous this work can be, even with
unobstructed vision, I referred Ross's statement to Bill Geering, Oz Deputy
CVO, and Mike Poidinger, University of Queensland, for comment. MHJ]
From: "Geering, Bill" <WAG@mailpc.brs.gov.au>
To: Martin Hugh-Jones <mehj2020@vt8200.vetmed.lsu.edu>
Subject: Ross Tancred and Q fever
Date: Thu, 27 Mar 97 13:38:00 PST
Q fever (Coxiella burnetii) is endemic in Australia, with the highest
prevalence probably being in the State of Queensland. Various hygiene
procedures are required to be carried out in abattoirs to reduce the level
of contamination, including restricting the opening of gravid uteri to
special rooms. Nevertheless, abattoir workers are at high occupational risk
of contracting _C. burnetii infection_. The Queensland Workplace Health and
Safety authorities have therefore established a policy which requires skin
testing and subsequent vaccination (where necessary) of new abattoir
employees; with a requirement that effective respirators (an approved face
mask) be worn by such employees in risk areas until two weeks after they
have been vaccinated, or testing has shown vaccination to be unnecessary.
Visitors are also required to wear respirators if going into risk areas of
abattoirs.
---
Bill Geering
Canberra
